Well now after seeing this olivia's profie I just couldn't waste this magnificant chance to procrastinate- my favourite hobby.

Style wise I guess I'm pretty ordinary, my clothes mainly consist of blue, black, grey and green. The occasional flash of yellow or tuquiose but apart from that I basically have afew colours which I cling to for security reasons.
column3:
Going onto security I was definity beginning to step outside the ""style"" box i.e. becoming an emo freak but unfortunatly or fortunatly depending on how you view it I have lulled back into my frankie jeans and whatever I can be fucked to put on top which is normally no more than a bra of some description whilst at university for fear of standing out. Now this may or may not surprise you depending on how well you know me and my contradictory nature, but fear of being judged on what I am wearing has always been prevelant particularly at university where first impressions last forever as I have been learning more and more as time has gone on.....

I guess that my stlye is never ""whats in"" nor is it so out there that its cool, I guess the combination of denim denim and denim wil do that coupled with a pair of ever comfy dolly shoes or ugg boots, and a basic strapy top or t. scarf is always a must have as is a spare top, a bag that hangs across your body if you will be buying anything and generally strange additions to my outfit such as hats which i have become a complete whore for.... thanks patrick.

Bascially my style is fairly masculine and comfortable, a little off the wall but mainly just a whole load of basics, bit like my personality really."

event,"A  man walked into the ladies department of a Macy 's and shyly walked up to
the woman behind the counter and said, ""I'd like to buy a bra for my  wife.""
What type of bra?"" asked the clerk.
Type?"" inquires the  man, ""There's more than one type?""
Look around,"" said the saleslady,  as she showed a sea of bras in every
shape, size, color and material  imaginable.
Actually,  even with all of this variety, there are really only four types
Relieved, the man asked about the types.
There are the Catholic, the Salvation Army, the  Presbyterian, and the
Now  totally befuddled, the man asked about the differences between them.
The Saleslady responded, ""It is all really quite simple...
The  Catholic type supports the masses.
The  Salvation Army type lifts the fallen,
The  Presbyterian type keeps them staunch and upright, and
The  Baptist makes mountains out of mole hills.
Have  you ever wondered why A, B, C, D, DD, E, F, G, and H are the letters
If you have wondered why, but couldn't figure out  what the letters stood
for, it is about time you became informed!

It happens to us all eventually. It doesn't matter who you are, one day you'll wake up and realise you haven't a clue what music the cool kids are listening to. Of course, some people are quite happy with this. They're probably too busy washing the car or perusing the new IKEA catalogue to even notice, let alone care.
For the rest of us, though, it's a sad day.

Thankfully, help is now at hand. We've teamed up with Channel 4 Radio to bring you a little primer of what's going down on the street - well, the playground and university common room anyway.This page will grow to become a crucial resource for anyone not ready for their pipe and slippers just yet. So if you think emo is that annoying puppet Rod Hull had (and it bothers you), you've come to the right place.

Emo is a genre of indie rock with its origins in Washington DC's mid-1980s hardcore punk scene. The first wave of emo bands shared some quite specific characteristics, notably a tendency for spontaneous emotional outbursts in performance, hence the name.

The sound was made more melodic by a new generation of indie-influenced bands in the mid-1990s, creating the conditions for its absorption into the mainstream. In truth, the term is now sufficiently broad to encompass a relatively wide range of music, leading to much debate as to who does and does not qualify as emo.

Kit yourself out from head to toe in black, die your hair the same colour, and ensure to brush as much of it over your face as possible. Finish off the look by painting your nails. A reaction against jock culture, Emo types shun anything sporty or overtly masculine.
Panic! At The Disco, My Chemical Romance, Fall Out Boy
My Sweet Nothing, Hiding With Girls, The Cape of Good Hope

Screamo is a sub-genre of new emo. Songs are often slower and more melodic than in other genres, less of a ""beatdown"" and more of an opportunity for introspection. Screamo has been described as ""mixing the literate, poetic lyrics of emo punk with a harsher and more metallic brand of sonic thrash, as well as using screaming vocals"".
Not too dissimilar to EMO in the sense that simple black clothing and a hatred of the mainstream are required.
JR Ewing, Bet On Black, Slapshock
Hot Cross, A Life In Vain and Action

The music is typified by sparse and minimalist 2step breakbeats, generally around 130-140 beats per minute, and a fast, aggressive rapping style - often in double time. The lyrics and music combine futuristic electronic elements and dark, growling bass lines.

Individual clothing, tattoos and piercings are all popular ways for grime lovers to express their music taste. Due to the aggressive nature of the music, grime fans are outspoken and fanatical about getting their point across. Rebellious types, grimers don't like being told what to do and will stand up against the system.
Dizzee Rascal, Garbage Gang, Element of Grime
